properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major low pressure system from the Great Lakes region will affect the province of Quebec on Thursday and Friday. This system could give the first significant amounts of snow over Northwestern and Central Quebec. Snowfall amounts could exceed 15 centimetres in several areas. At this time, there is still uncertainty with regard to the track of this system, which may have an impact on the amounts of snow to be received and the affected regions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Ste. Agathe, Emerson, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potentially significant rainfall this evening through Friday morning. A low pressure system will approach Southern Ontario from the southwest. Rain is forecast to begin this evening and end by Friday afternoon. Rainfall amounts of 30 to 50 mm are possible, with the heaviest rain occurring Thursday afternoon. Strong westerly wind gusts of 90 km/h are possible overnight Thursday into Friday afternoon. A wind warning may be required as conditions become more certain. If visibility is reduced during driving, turn on headlights and maintain a safe following distance. Remember pedestrians are more difficult to see when it is dark and raining. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major low pressure system from the Great Lakes will affect the province of Quebec on Thursday and Friday. This system will bring heavy rain and strong winds. Total rainfall amounts could exceed 50 millimetres and winds may reach up to 90 kilometres per hour. Heavy rain may cause flash floods and ponding on roads. Please put away or secure any objects that could be damaged or moved by the wind. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Two periods of snow are expected by Saturday morning including possibly a significant snowfall Friday night. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm between Thursday afternoon and early Friday morning. 15 cm or more between Friday afternoon and early Saturday morning. Maximum wind gusts: 70 km/h or higher Friday night. Locations: Along the coast from Rigolet to Lodge Bay, and inland to Churchill Valley. Timespan: Thursday afternoon through early Saturday morning. Remarks: Snow is expect for a large portion of Labrador beginning Thursday afternoon and again on Friday afternoon. The snowfall on Friday could possibly be significant and be accompanied by high winds. Conditions will improve on Saturday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rain expected for New Brunswick on Thursday and Friday... A low pressure system will begin to approach the Maritimes from the west on Thursday. Widespread rain is expected to begin over New Brunswick by Thursday morning then increase in intensity Thursday night and into Friday. Current indications suggest that total rainfall accumulations will be in the range of 40 to 80 mm over western New Brunswick by the time the rain ends on Friday afternoon. Lesser accumulations are expected over eastern portions of the province. There will also be strong south to southwest winds accompanying this system later on Thursday and into Friday. The public is advised to monitor future forecasts as warnings may be required. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-30T23:50:24-00:00
